      "name": "How many days can you spend in Georgia (the US state) without becoming a resident?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Fewer than 183 days in any 12-consecutive-month period. Once you have resided in Georgia for 183 days or more, counted in the aggregate over the immediately preceding 365 days, you are treated as a resident individual for state income tax. The window is rolling, so it does not reset on 1 January."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Is Georgia's rule based on a calendar year like most US states?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "No. Georgia counts 183 days across the immediately preceding 365 days measured to income tax day, so the relevant window is any 12 consecutive months rather than a fixed 1 January to 31 December calendar year. Days do not have to be consecutive and are counted in the aggregate."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Do you need a home in Georgia to be caught by the 183-day rule?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "No. Unlike states that require a permanent place of abode, Georgia's 183-day test turns on physical presence alone. Residing in the state for 183 days over the preceding 12 months makes you a resident individual even without owning or renting a home there."
      }
    }
  ]
}

