        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Up to 200 days in the taxable year. Spending more than 200 days in Hawaii, counted in the aggregate over the year, creates a rebuttable presumption that you were a resident of Hawaii from the time of your arrival. Exactly 200 days does not trigger the presumption."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Can you rebut Hawaii's 200-day presumption?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Yes. The presumption is rebuttable. You can overcome it with evidence satisfactory to the Hawaii Department of Taxation that you maintain a permanent place of abode outside Hawaii and were in Hawaii only for a temporary or transitory purpose."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Do the 200 days in Hawaii have to be consecutive?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "No. The days are counted in the aggregate across the taxable year and do not need to be consecutive. Every day you are present in Hawaii adds to the total that is measured against the 200-day line."
      }
    }
  ]
}

