        "text": "Up to 200 days in the tax year. Spending more than 200 days in Oregon while maintaining a place of abode there makes you a resident, even if you are domiciled elsewhere, unless you can prove your presence was only temporary or transitory. Exactly 200 days keeps you under the day test."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What counts as a day in Oregon for the 200-day rule?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Any fraction of a calendar day spent in Oregon is counted as a whole day. Days do not need to be consecutive, and you do not need to sleep at your Oregon place of abode for the day to count."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Do you need a home in Oregon to be a statutory resident?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Yes. The 200-day test requires both a permanent place of abode maintained in Oregon and more than 200 days in the state during the tax year. Days alone, without a place of abode, do not trigger this test, though separate domicile rules can still make you a resident."
      }
    }
  ]
}

