      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "How many days can you stay in Portugal without becoming a tax resident?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Up to 183 days in any rolling 12-month period. Spending more than 183 days in Portugal within any 12-month window can make you a tax resident under the day-count test. A separate habitual-residence test can also apply if you keep a home there."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Is Portugal's 183-day rule based on the calendar year?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "No. It is measured across any rolling 12-month period, not the January-to-December calendar year. A stay split across two calendar years can still cross 183 days inside a single 12-month window."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Can you be a Portuguese tax resident with fewer than 183 days?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Yes. Portugal can also treat you as resident if you have a home there on any day of the 12-month period in conditions suggesting you intend to keep and occupy it as your habitual residence. The day count is only one of the tests."
      }
    }
  ]
}

