      "name": "How many days can you stay in Thailand without becoming a tax resident?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Up to 180 days in a calendar year. If your days present in Thailand aggregate to more than 180 in a single tax (calendar) year, you are deemed a Thai tax resident for that year. The days do not need to be consecutive."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Is Thailand's 180-day rule based on the calendar year?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Yes. Thailand's tax year is the calendar year, and the days present are added up across 1 January to 31 December. The count resets each new calendar year, and days do not need to be consecutive to add up to more than 180."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Does becoming a Thai tax resident affect foreign income?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Yes. A Thai tax resident is taxed on income from Thai sources and, under rules effective from 2024, on foreign-sourced income that is brought into Thailand. A non-resident is generally taxed only on Thai-source income, so crossing 180 days changes what Thailand can tax."
      }
    }
  ]
}

